Business Problem

Mark is an Actuary working in an auto insurance industry “Your Insurance inc”.In order to help assess risk of the autos being insured, he has approached the Analytics team to predict the risk level of any new autos based on the past data available with the business. You are part of the Analytics team and would need to come up with a model and solution to help business with prediction of the risk factor.

Known Information: We need to identify and Predict Risk Factor of a car Insurance company.

Choosing Models

Machine Learning is classified in to two types, 1. Supervised Learning 2. UnSupervised Learning

Unsupervised Learning: Incase, If there is no dependent variable, then it comes under unsupervised learning. We can perform clustering and get insights from visualization for this type of problem.

Supervised Learning: Whenever we encounter Dependent variable, then it clearly shows that it is supervised learning, We are predicting the dependent variable with the help of independent variable. So as our data set has dependent variable, It clearly shows we need to perform supervised learning models.

Under Supervised learning there are two types of operation can be performed. 1. Regression Type Models 2. Classification Type Models Those models can be determined only based on dependent variable.

If the dependent variable is continuous(numerical and different values), Then we need to go for regression models else we need to go for classification type models when we have classes(yes or no)

As we see, Out dataset has factor variable which has 6 classes (-2, -1, 0, 1, 2, 3). So we need to use Classification Type Models.

There are different Classification type Models like 1. Logistic Regression 2. Decision Tree Classification 3. Random Forest Classification 4. Support Vector Machine 5. KNN Classification

We need to model various models and we need to check the accuracy.

As of now, Dependent Variable : RiskFactor Independent Variable: All Variable expect RiskFactor

Performing Exploratory Data Analysis

Exploratory Data Analysis is the important part of any machine learning process. We need to prepare the data for processing into the algorithm. There are majorly used steps list below:

  1. Uni Variant Analysis Analysing about each and every variables, its behavior, its skewness etc

  2. Bi Variant Analysis Analysing two different variables with each others. it check its behavior or significance level for modelling Example: Plotting a graph between Price of Car (Independent Variable) and Risk Factor(Dependent Variable), if it is significant enough we can have those column else we can remove that insiginificant columns

  3. Missing Values and its Treatment Missing values is one of the important aspect which need to be treated before starting modelling because it may cause moisy and misguide model There are various methods to impute Missing values
  4. Mean
  5. Median
  6. Mode
  7. Using Predictions like KNN Algorithm or Decision Tree for predicting missing values

  8. Else we can remove that particular column as well (But there will be data loss)

  9. Outlier Detection and its treatment Similar to missing values outlier values need to be treated before modelling to get better accuracy. Outlier Treatment is also similar to missing values treatment.

  10. Feature Engineering There are two important sub categories available,

  11. Feature Selection: This enables us to select the important variables for modelling, Because when ever we impute unwanted variable for modelling the accuracy will be affected and So we need to minimize the number of variables need to be used for modelling.

Example: Boruta Algorithm enables us to know which variables ae unimportant so that we can remove from dataset.

  1. Feature Creation Creating a column from the exists column which helps in more accuracy. There are different types of feature creation like,
    1. Binning
    2. Dummy Variable Creation

So, Lets go into Exploratory data Analysis part now, There is no thumb in the order.

Outlier Treatment is very important because Outlier may cause deviation in Mean and Median values which affects the output of the predictions

MultiCollinearity Issue - Solving it

Multi Collinearity can be solved by many methods like Priciple Component Analysis Factor Analysis Ridge Regression Lasso Regression

But as the Categorical variable are grouped with continuous variable in same data set.

I have applying VIF - Variable Inflation Factor to eliminate Correlated Variable.

Buliding Models using various Machine Learning Algorithm using Cross Validation

Models used are listed below:

  1. Support Vector Machine
  2. Random Forest classification
  3. Decision Tree Classification

    2. Using rpart Algorithm
  4. Logistics Regression

Lets compare the various models accuracy and improve its tuning parameters as well.

Predicting both Insample Prediction and Outsample Prediction. Insample Prediction: Predicting the train data itself which we used to build model Outsample Prediction: Predicting the test data for which we need to check accuracy

Cross Validation

Sometimes prediction may work well in training set but accuracy will be very low in test set which cause overfitting issue. To resolve this issue, cross validation helps us.

We can split the data in to blocks and we can calculate accuracy for each and every blocks and by using it we can also predict the overall accuracy.

Split every block with 10% of data, and adding top 3 accuracy blocks as test set and remaining as training set.

1. Support Vector Machine

Ins_folds$Fold01
##  [1]   6  24  55  57  65  67  75  84  96 130 131 139 142 147 167 176 193
## [18] 194 198
SVM_CrossValidation = lapply(Ins_folds,function(x) {
  Ins_train_fold = sample_Scaled[-x,]
  Ins_test_fold = sample_Scaled[x,]
  Ins_classifier = svm(RiskFactor~., data=  Ins_train_fold)
  Ins_pred = predict(Ins_classifier,Ins_test_fold[-19])
  return(confusionMatrix(Ins_test_fold[,19],Ins_pred))
  })
print(SVM_CrossValidation) #Gets Summary for different 10 folds

#Finding Best fold for Modelling to avoid over fitting
library(caret)
library(e1071)
library(C50)
#install.packages("rpart")
library(rpart)
set.seed(123)
rpart_folds = createFolds(sample_Scaled$RiskFactor, k=10)

rpart_CrossValidation = lapply(rpart_folds,function(x) {
  rpart_train_fold = sample_Scaled[-x,]
  rpart_test_fold = sample_Scaled[x,]
  rpart_classifier = C5.0(RiskFactor~., data = rpart_train_fold)
  rpart_pred = predict(rpart_classifier,rpart_test_fold[-19],type = "class")
  return(confusionMatrix(rpart_test_fold[,19],rpart_pred))
  #  accuracy = (cm[1,1]+cm[2,2]+cm[3,3]+cm[4,4]+cm[5,5]+cm[6,6])/(sum(cm))
  #  return(accuracy)
  #  return(cm)
})

Conclusion:

For the given data, C5.0 Decision Tree models performs better than other modelling But while Comparing the overall Accuracy value, performance of c5.0 is very less than Random Forest algorithm, which implies only particular block data gives better results in Decision tree but all test data blocks gives good amount accuracy in random forest.

When we use Decision tree, there is a chance of Overfitting because it may have more accuracy but it wont be having same accuracy for newly predicting outcomes as its overall accuracy is very low.

But random forest has very good overall accuracy, where the overfitting problem wont exist in this case.

So, For the mentioned dataset, Random Forest modelling works well for predicting new test data
